## Prepare dataset for training model:
if train:
    filenames = os.listdir(os.path.join(imgDir, "train"))
    print(len(filenames), "images found")
    ## get category from each image
    df = pd.DataFrame({
        'filename':filenames,
#         'category':pd.Series(filenames).str.split("_", expand=True)[1].str.slice(0,2)
        'category':pd.Series(filenames).str[-10:-8]
    })
    ## filter to image with EN and ZN
    df = df.loc[(df['category'] == 'EN')| (df['category'] == 'ZN')]
    df = df.sample(1000)
    print("Training on", df.shape[0], "images")
    print("categories:\n", df.category.value_counts())
   
    ## Create model
    from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
    from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D,MaxPooling2D,\
         Dropout,Flatten,Dense,Activation,\
         BatchNormalization

    # sequential (not recursive) model (one input, one output)
    model=Sequential()

    ## First convolutional layer with 4 filters (kernels)
    model.add(Conv2D(4, 3, activation='relu',
                     input_shape=(imageWidth, imageHeight, imgChannels)))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))

    ## 2nd convolutional layer
    model.add(Conv2D(8, 3, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))
    
    ## 3rd convolutional layer
    model.add(Conv2D(16, 3, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))
    ## Flatten the image into a string of pixels
    model.add(Flatten())
    ## Use one final dense layer
    model.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    
    model.add(Dense(8, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))
    
    ## Output layer with 2 softmax nodes
    model.add(Dense(2, activation='softmax'))
    #model.add(Dense(5, activation='softmax'))


    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  optimizer='rmsprop',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

    model.summary()
    
    ## Training data generator:
    train_generator = ImageDataGenerator(
        rescale=1./255
    ).\
    flow_from_dataframe(
        df,
        os.path.join(imgDir, "train"),
        x_col='filename', y_col='category',
        target_size=imageSize,
        class_mode='categorical',
        color_mode="grayscale",
        batch_size=batch_size)

    ## Model Training:
    history = model.fit(
        train_generator,
        epochs=epochs
    )

    ##  Save the model:
    print("Save model to {}".format(modelFName))
    model.save(modelFName)
    # end of training

else:
    ## No training, just load model
    print("Load model from {}".format(modelFName))
    model = tf.keras.models.load_model(modelFName)

The ZN EN model¶

The ZN/EN to test my model so far which is the easiest one to get high accuracy has the accuracy of 100% (swing from 99.5% to 100%)with 1000 images and 200 validation files, which I used the 30 epochs with a batch size of 30. The reason that I did not use the full dataset is that my computer was so slow that it may take 10 minutes per step.

Initially, I used the epochs with small numbers such as 2 to start with since in general, the smaller batch size renders better training accuracy, stability, and generalization performance. However, the time to process is slow at 26ms/step since my computer is not good enough, and it might take longer when my computer loaded other stuff at the same time. With epochs of 2, the accuracy was low around 60%. Then, I increased the epoch size to 30, and higher accuracy presented with around 80% but the speed is slow (26ms/steps*30epochs to process). Therefore, I increased the epoch size to 30, which gave higher accuracy when the epoch went higher. I tried to change and increase the batch by 30, which renders the best result of accuracy with 100%. Even though a higher epoch renders higher accuracy, the longer time that train model to process and the model might be overfitting.

When I used a large filter size in each layer (example code), the parameter was high with a number of around 3 million. If the parameters are too high, it causes the larger networks slow and overfitting. Thus, in order to decrease the parameter, I needed to decrease the weights of each layer in the training model by decreasing the filter size due to the reason that the parameters are the sum of the number of weights of the layers + the number of biases of layers.

batch_size = 32
epochs = 2
## Prepare dataset for training model:
if train:
    filenames = os.listdir(os.path.join(imgDir, "train"))
    print(len(filenames), "images found")
    ## get category from each image
    df = pd.DataFrame({
        'filename':filenames,
#         'category':pd.Series(filenames).str.split("_", expand=True)[1].str.slice(0,2)
        'category':pd.Series(filenames).str[-10:-8]
    })
    ## filter to image with EN and ZN
    df = df.loc[(df['category'] == 'EN')| (df['category'] == 'ZN') | (df['category'] == 'TH') ]
    df = df.sample(1000)
    print("Training on", df.shape[0], "images")
    print("categories:\n", df.category.value_counts())
   
    ## Create model
    from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
    from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D,MaxPooling2D,\
         Dropout,Flatten,Dense,Activation,\
         BatchNormalization

    # sequential (not recursive) model (one input, one output)
    model=Sequential()

    ## First convolutional layer with 16 filters (kernels)
    model.add(Conv2D(16, 3, activation='relu',
                     input_shape=(imageWidth, imageHeight, imgChannels)))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))
    
    ## 2nd convolutional layer
    model.add(Conv2D(32, 3, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))
    
    ## 3rd convolutional layer
    model.add(Conv2D(64, 3, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))
    
    model.add(Conv2D(128, 3, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))
   
    ## Flatten the image into a string of pixels
    model.add(Flatten())
    ## Use one final dense layer
    model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    
    model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    
    ## Output layer with 2 softmax nodes
    model.add(Dense(3, activation='softmax'))

                  optimizer='rmsprop',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

        rescale=1./255

    flow_from_dataframe(

from PIL import Image
train_filenames = os.listdir(os.path.join(imgDir, "train"))
test_filenames = os.listdir(os.path.join(imgDir, "validation"))
save = False
train = [os.path.join(imgDir, "train") + "/" + f for f in train_filenames]
test = [os.path.join(imgDir, "validation") + "/" + f for f in test_filenames]
filenames = train + test
if save:
    for f in filenames:
        input_img = Image.open(f,mode='r')
        left = 20
        top = 20
        right = 180
        bot = 180
        f_name = 'language/' + f.split("/")[1] + "_resized/" + f.split("/")[2]
        output_img = input_img.crop((left, top, right, bot))
        output_img = output_img.save(f_name)
else:
    print("Image already resized")

## Prepare dataset for training model:
batch_size = 32
epochs = 10

if train:
    filenames = os.listdir(os.path.join(imgDir, "train"))
    print(len(filenames), "images found")
    ## get category from each image
    df = pd.DataFrame({
        'filename':filenames,
#         'category':pd.Series(filenames).str.split("_", expand=True)[1].str.slice(0,2)
        'category':pd.Series(filenames).str[-10:-8]
    })
    ## filter to image with EN and ZN
    df = df.loc[(df['category'] == 'EN')| (df['category'] == 'DA')]
    df = df.sample(1000)
    print("Training on", df.shape[0], "images")
    print("categories:\n", df.category.value_counts())
   
    ## Create model
    from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
    from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv2D,MaxPooling2D,\
         Dropout,Flatten,Dense,Activation,\
         BatchNormalization

    # sequential (not recursive) model (one input, one output)
    model=Sequential()

    ## First convolutional layer with 4 filters (kernels)
    model.add(Conv2D(4, 3, activation='relu',
                     input_shape=(imageWidth, imageHeight, imgChannels)))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))

    ## 2nd convolutional layer
    model.add(Conv2D(8, 3, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))
    
    ## 3rd convolutional layer
    model.add(Conv2D(16, 3, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=2))
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))
    ## Flatten the image into a string of pixels
    model.add(Flatten())
    ## Use one final dense layer
    model.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dropout(0.5))
    
    model.add(Dense(8, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Dropout(0.25))
    
    ## Output layer with 2 softmax nodes
    model.add(Dense(2, activation='softmax'))
    #model.add(Dense(5, activation='softmax'))


    model.compile(loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  optimizer='rmsprop',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

    model.summary()
    
    ## Training data generator:
    train_generator = ImageDataGenerator(
        rescale=1./255
    ).\
    flow_from_dataframe(
        df,
        os.path.join(imgDir, "train"),
        x_col='filename', y_col='category',
        target_size=imageSize,
        class_mode='categorical',
        color_mode="grayscale",
        batch_size=batch_size)

    ## Model Training:
    history = model.fit(
        train_generator,
        epochs=epochs
    )

    ##  Save the model:
    print("Save model to {}".format(modelFName))
    model.save(modelFName)
    # end of training

else:
    ## No training, just load model
    print("Load model from {}".format(modelFName))
    model = tf.keras.models.load_model(modelFName)

When I changed the filter number, the accuracy smaller and I am not sure which direction that I should looked into it more.

    model=Sequential()

                     input_shape=(imageWidth, imageHeight, imgChannels)))

print(pd.crosstab(validationResults.category, validationResults.predicted))
print("Accuracy", np.mean(validationResults.category == validationResults.predicted))

Interpretation¶
